  {
    "type": "Question",
    "name": "Question 3 @ 2022/2023",
    "Question": {
      "content": "The following are the properties of electric charges",
      "type": "OBJ",
      "options": [
        "charges are conserved",
        "charges are quantized",
        "all of the above",
        "none of the above"
      ]
    },
    "Answer": {
      "type": "string",
      "content": "all of the above"
    },
    "Explanation": {
      "type": "string",
      "content": "<div style='font-family: Arial, sans-serif; line-height: 1.6;'><h3 style='color: #2c3e50;'>Fundamental Properties of Electric Charge</h3><h4 style='color: #2c3e50; margin-top: 15px;'>1. Charge Conservation</h4><p>In any closed system, the <strong>total charge remains constant</strong>. Charge cannot be created or destroyed, only transferred.</p><h4 style='color: #2c3e50;'>2. Charge Quantization</h4><p>Charge exists in <strong>discrete multiples</strong> of the elementary charge (<em>e</em> ≈ 1.6 × 10<sup>−19</sup> C). For example, electrons have −<em>e</em>, protons +<em>e</em>.</p><h4 style='color: #2c3e50;'>Conclusion</h4><p>Since <strong>both properties are true</strong>, the correct answer is <strong>all of the above</strong>.</p></div>"
    },
    "topic": [
      "Electrostatics",
      "Electric Charges"
    ]
  },
  {
    "type": "Question",
    "name": "Question 5 @ 2022/2023",
    "Question": {
      "content": "What is the force between two positive charges 100µC and 200µC when it is separated by a distance of 3 cm",
      "type": "OBJ",
      "options": [
        "20N",
        "2 x 10¹¹N",
        "2x10⁵N",
        "6x10³N"
      ]
    },
    "Answer": {
      "type": "string",
      "content": "2x10⁵N"
    },
    "Explanation": {
      "type": "string",
      "content": "<div style='font-family: Arial, sans-serif; line-height: 1.6;'><h3 style='color: #2c3e50;'>Coulomb's Law Calculation</h3><p>The electrostatic force between two point charges is given by:</p><p style='background: #f8f9fa; padding: 10px; border-left: 4px solid #3498db;'><strong>F = k(q₁q₂)/r²</strong></p><p>Where:</p><ul><li><strong>k</strong> (Coulomb's constant) ≈ 9 × 10<sup>9</sup> Nm²/C²</li><li><strong>q₁</strong> = 100 µC = 100 × 10<sup>-6</sup> C</li><li><strong>q₂</strong> = 200 µC = 200 × 10<sup>-6</sup> C</li><li><strong>r</strong> = 3 cm = 0.03 m</li></ul><h4 style='color: #2c3e50; margin-top: 15px;'>Step-by-Step Solution:</h4><p><strong>1. Calculate q₁ × q₂:</strong><br>100 × 10<sup>-6</sup> C × 200 × 10<sup>-6</sup> C = 2 × 10<sup>-8</sup> C²</p><p><strong>2. Calculate r²:</strong><br>(0.03 m)² = 0.0009 m²</p><p><strong>3. Apply Coulomb's Law:</strong><br>F = (9 × 10<sup>9</sup>) × (2 × 10<sup>-8</sup>)/0.0009</p><p><strong>4. Simplify:</strong><br>= (9 × 10<sup>9</sup>) × (2/9) × 10<sup>-4</sup><br>= 2 × 10<sup>5</sup> N</p><p>Thus, the force is <strong>2 × 10⁵ N</strong>.</p></div>"
    },
    "topic": [
      "Electrostatics",
      "Electric Charges",
      "Coulomb's Law",
      "Physics"
    ]
  },
  {
    "type": "Question",
    "name": "Question 11 @ 2022/2023",
    "Question": {
      "content": "When a 5nC test is placed at a point, it experiences a force of \\( 2 \\times 10^{-4} N \\). What is the electric field E at that point?",
      "type": "OBJ",
      "options": [
        "4 x 10⁵N/C",
        "4 x 10⁴N/C",
        "4 x 10⁵N/C",
        "4 x 10⁴N/C"
      ]
    },
    "Answer": {
      "type": "string",
      "content": "4 × 10⁴ N/C"
    },
    "Explanation": {
      "type": "string",
      "content": "<div><h3>Step-by-Step Explanation:</h3><ol><li><strong>Given:</strong><ul><li>Test charge, \\( q = 5 \\, \\text{nC} = 5 \\times 10^{-9} \\, \\text{C} \\)</li><li>Force experienced, \\( F = 2 \\times 10^{-4} \\, \\text{N} \\)</li></ul></li><li><strong>Formula:</strong> The electric field \\( E \\) is calculated using:<br>\\[ E = \\frac{F}{q} \\]</li><li><strong>Substitute values:</strong><br>\\[ E = \\frac{2 \\times 10^{-4} \\, \\text{N}}{5 \\times 10^{-9} \\, \\text{C}} \\]</li><li><strong>Simplify:</strong><ul><li>Divide the coefficients: \\( \\frac{2}{5} = 0.4 \\)</li><li>Subtract exponents: \\( 10^{-4 - (-9)} = 10^{5} \\)</li><li>Thus, \\( E = 0.4 \\times 10^{5} \\, \\text{N/C} \\)</li></ul></li><li><strong>Express in scientific notation:</strong><br>\\[ E = 4 \\times 10^{4} \\, \\text{N/C} \\]</li><li><strong>Conclusion:</strong> The electric field at the point is \\( 4 \\times 10^{4} \\, \\text{N/C} \\), which matches options <strong>b</strong> and <strong>d</strong>.</li></ol></div>"
    },
